nán is not a grammaticalized marker of definiteness but it is used in various context for identifying entities which have been activitated in previous discourse. Since an example from a text would need too much space, the example given here is taken from Iwasaki & Ingkaphirom (2007). The definite interpretation of this passage is mine (W.B.).
In this function, lǎŋ 'back' is only used metaphorically in fixed expressions.
'finish' (stop doing for the time being; finish for good, being through with sth.)
There is also the verb còp 'finish (for good)'. When used in COMPLETIVE function, it indicates that a given action is completed for good.

Target Meaning also: COMITATIVE marker; This is a rather weak form of expressing instrumental because the meaning of 'take' is still present. The most prototypical expression for instrumentals is the preposition dûay 'with' as in dûay mîit 'with a knife'.
Also cf. expressions like: naan-maa-lɛ́ew [long (of time) -come-PFV] 'a long time since'
In this function, tham 'do' is only used with a limited set of stative verbs.
Hây is only used with dynamic verbs. It still has many properties of a control verb.
This construction can be seen as a special case of desiderative construction (cf. Rangkupan 2007: 229).
